00:19:23,480 --> 00:19:24,760
Hmm?

397
00:19:34,520 --> 00:19:35,640
Oh!

398
00:19:37,080 --> 00:19:39,680
Hm. Mm.

399
00:19:39,720 --> 00:19:41,640
Oh, hello, Mrs. Premise.

400
00:19:41,680 --> 00:19:44,240
Hello, Mrs. Conclusion.

401
00:19:44,280 --> 00:19:46,000
-Busy day?
-Busy?

402
00:19:46,040 --> 00:19:49,600
I just spent four hours
burying the cat.

403
00:19:49,640 --> 00:19:51,560
Four hours to bury a cat?

404
00:19:51,600 --> 00:19:53,240
Yes. It wouldn't keep still.

405
00:19:53,280 --> 00:19:56,000
Wiggling around,
howling its head off.

406
00:19:56,040 --> 00:19:57,720
Oh, it wasn't dead,
then?

407
00:19:57,760 --> 00:20:00,520
Well, no, no,
but it's not at all
a well cat.

408
00:20:00,560 --> 00:20:03,320
So, uh, as we were going away
for a fortnight's holiday

409
00:20:03,360 --> 00:20:05,920
I thought I better bury it
just to be on the safe side.

410
00:20:05,960 --> 00:20:07,440
Quite right.
You don't want

411
00:20:07,480 --> 00:20:09,920
to come back from Sorrento
to a dead cat.

412
00:20:09,960 --> 00:20:12,480
-Nope.
-It'd be so anticlimactic.

413
00:20:12,520 --> 00:20:14,600
Yes, kill it now,
that's what I say.

414
00:20:14,640 --> 00:20:18,000
-Yes.
-We're going to have to have
our budgie put down.

415
00:20:18,040 --> 00:20:20,200
Really? Is it very old?

416
00:20:20,240 --> 00:20:22,720
No. We just don't like it.

417
00:20:22,760 --> 00:20:24,960
We're going to take it
to the vet tomorrow.

418
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:27,400
Oh. Tell me, how do they
put budgies down, then?

419
00:20:27,440 --> 00:20:29,000
Well, it's funny
you should ask that

420
00:20:29,040 --> 00:20:30,800
because I've just been reading
a great big book

421
00:20:30,840 --> 00:20:33,360
about how to put
your budgie down.

422
00:20:33,400 --> 00:20:36,640
And apparently, you can either
hit them with a book

423
00:20:36,680 --> 00:20:39,640
or you can shoot them
just there,
just above the beak.

424
00:20:39,680 --> 00:20:41,000
-Just there?
-Yes.

425
00:20:41,040 --> 00:20:42,880
-Well, well, well.
-Mm.

426
00:20:42,920 --> 00:20:45,200
Of course, Mrs. Essence
flushed hers down the loo.

427
00:20:45,240 --> 00:20:49,280
Oh! No, you shouldn't do that.
No, that's dangerous.

428
00:20:49,320 --> 00:20:52,320
Yes, they breed in the sewers.

429
00:20:52,360 --> 00:20:54,560
Yes, eventually
you get evil-smelling flocks

430
00:20:54,600 --> 00:20:58,160
of huge soiled budgies flying
out of people's lavatories,

431
00:20:58,200 --> 00:21:01,680
infringing their personal
freedom.

432
00:21:01,720 --> 00:21:03,120
Good morning, Mrs. Cutout.

433
00:21:03,160 --> 00:21:04,760
Morning, Mrs. Cutout.

434
00:21:06,520 --> 00:21:08,240
-It's a funny thing, freedom.
-Yes.

435
00:21:08,280 --> 00:21:09,920
I mean, how can any of us
be really free

436
00:21:09,960 --> 00:21:11,840
when we still have
personal possessions?

437
00:21:11,880 --> 00:21:15,360
You can't. You can't. How can
I go off and join FRELIMO

438
00:21:15,400 --> 00:21:17,640
when I've got nine more
installments to pay
on the fridge?

439
00:21:17,680 --> 00:21:19,120
-No, you can't.
-No.

440
00:21:19,160 --> 00:21:20,680
Well, this, of course,
is the whole crux

441
00:21:20,720 --> 00:21:22,560
of Jean-Paul Sartre's
<i>Roads to Freedom.</i>

442
00:21:22,600 --> 00:21:24,360
No, it bloody isn't.

443
00:21:25,760 --> 00:21:28,240
The nub of that is, his
characters stand for all of us

444
00:21:28,280 --> 00:21:30,160
in their desire
to avoid action.

445
00:21:30,200 --> 00:21:32,000
Mind you,
the man at the
off-license says

446
00:21:32,040 --> 00:21:33,880
it's an everyday story
of French country folk.

447
00:21:33,920 --> 00:21:35,680
-What does he know?
-Nothing.

448
00:21:35,720 --> 00:21:39,080
Sixty new pence for a bottle
of Maltese claret.

449
00:21:39,120 --> 00:21:41,600
-Mm.
-Ha! Well, I personally think--

450
00:21:41,640 --> 00:21:43,880
Oh, beg your pardon.
I personally think

451
00:21:43,920 --> 00:21:45,840
that Jean-Paul's masterwork
is an allegory

452
00:21:45,880 --> 00:21:47,320
of man's search
for commitment.

453
00:21:47,360 --> 00:21:48,720
-No, it isn't.
-Yes, it is.

454
00:21:48,760 --> 00:21:50,280
-Isn't. No, it isn't!
-'Tis.

455
00:21:50,320 --> 00:21:51,880
All right.
We'll soon settle this.

456
00:21:51,920 --> 00:21:53,160
We'll ask him.

457
00:21:53,200 --> 00:21:54,680
-Do you know him?
-Yes.

458
00:21:54,720 --> 00:21:56,280
We met on holiday
last year.

459
00:21:56,320 --> 00:21:57,960
-In Ibiza?
-Yes.

460
00:21:58,000 --> 00:21:59,400
He was staying there
with his wife

461
00:21:59,440 --> 00:22:01,280
and Mr. and Mr. Genet.

462
00:22:01,320 --> 00:22:04,040
Oh, I did get on well
with Madame S.

