00:22:05,720 --> 00:22:07,440
What was Jean-Paul like?

465
00:22:07,480 --> 00:22:09,200
Well, you know,
a bit moody.

466
00:22:09,240 --> 00:22:11,160
-Yes.
-Yes, he didn't join
in the fun much.

467
00:22:11,200 --> 00:22:12,840
-No.
-Just sat there, thinking.

468
00:22:12,880 --> 00:22:14,680
Still, Mr. Rotter caught him
a few times

469
00:22:14,720 --> 00:22:15,880
with a whoopee cushion.

470
00:22:15,920 --> 00:22:18,040
[BOTH LAUGH]

471
00:22:18,080 --> 00:22:21,360
[SPEAKS FRENCH]

472
00:22:21,400 --> 00:22:23,360
-[IMITATES FARTING]
-[BOTH LAUGH]

473
00:22:23,400 --> 00:22:26,160
-Oh, we did laugh.
-Oh, dear.

474
00:22:26,200 --> 00:22:28,080
Uh, well, we'll give him
a tinkle, then.

475
00:22:28,120 --> 00:22:29,960
Yes, all right.
She said they were
in the book.

476
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:33,120
Hmm-- Oh! Where's the Paris
telephone directory?

477
00:22:33,160 --> 00:22:35,240
MRS. INFERENCE:
It's on the dryer.

478
00:22:35,280 --> 00:22:38,880
Oh. No, no, that's Budapest.
Oh, here we are.

479
00:22:38,920 --> 00:22:40,880
Sartre, Sartre...

480
00:22:40,920 --> 00:22:43,960
It's 621036.

481
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:46,560
Oh, thank you, Mrs. Varley.

482
00:22:46,600 --> 00:22:51,240
Hello. Uh, Paris 621036,
please, and make it snappy,
buster.

483
00:22:52,800 --> 00:22:55,680
[BOTH SING IN FRENCH]

484
00:23:01,120 --> 00:23:05,640
Hello? Hello, Mrs. Sartre.
It's Beulagh Premise here.

485
00:23:05,680 --> 00:23:08,720
Oh, pardon.
<i>C'est</i> Beulagh Premise<i> ici.</i>

486
00:23:08,760 --> 00:23:12,120
<i>Oui! Oui! Dans</i> Ibiza.
<i>Oui.</i>

487
00:23:12,160 --> 00:23:13,240
Uh, we met--

488
00:23:13,280 --> 00:23:14,640
[SPEAKS FRENCH]

489
00:23:14,680 --> 00:23:16,800
Hotel Mirimar.

490
00:23:16,840 --> 00:23:18,520
<i>Oui! A la</i> barbecue.

491
00:23:18,560 --> 00:23:20,840
<i>C'est vrai. Madame S.,</i>

492
00:23:20,880 --> 00:23:24,320
<i>est-ce que Jean-Paul</i>
<i>est chez vous ?</i>

493
00:23:24,360 --> 00:23:26,320
<i>Oh, merde.</i>

494
00:23:26,360 --> 00:23:27,840
Well...

495
00:23:29,800 --> 00:23:31,520
Uh, when will he be free?

496
00:23:31,560 --> 00:23:34,520
[SPEAKS FRENCH]

497
00:23:34,560 --> 00:23:36,400
[CACKLES]
Oh!

498
00:23:38,080 --> 00:23:39,680
She says he's spent
the last 60 years

499
00:23:39,720 --> 00:23:41,280
trying to work that one out.

500
00:23:41,320 --> 00:23:43,600
[BOTH LAUGH]

501
00:23:43,640 --> 00:23:45,760
[SPEAKS FRENCH]

502
00:23:51,080 --> 00:23:54,040
Well, he's out distributing
pamphlets to the masses,

503
00:23:54,080 --> 00:23:55,920
but he'll be in at six.

504
00:23:55,960 --> 00:23:57,520
Oh, well, I'll ring BEA then.

505
00:23:57,560 --> 00:24:00,360
Oh, look, Paris!

506
00:24:01,760 --> 00:24:03,000
MRS. CONCLUSION:
That's not Paris.

507
00:24:03,040 --> 00:24:05,520
Jean-Paul wouldn't live here.

508
00:24:05,560 --> 00:24:07,320
It's a right old dump.

509
00:24:11,960 --> 00:24:14,480
But this is where
they were wrong.

510
00:24:14,520 --> 00:24:18,520
For this was no old dump,
but a town with a future.

511
00:24:18,560 --> 00:24:21,640
An urban El Dorado
where the businessmen of today

512
00:24:21,680 --> 00:24:24,280
can enjoy the facilities
of tomorrow

513
00:24:24,320 --> 00:24:26,280
in the comfort of yesterday.

514
00:24:26,320 --> 00:24:29,240
Provided by a go-getting,
go-ahead council

515
00:24:29,280 --> 00:24:32,520
who know just how loud
money can talk.

516
00:24:32,560 --> 00:24:33,760
Interest rates--

517
00:24:33,800 --> 00:24:35,720
Well, it's none of my
business,

518
00:24:35,760 --> 00:24:37,400
but we had the same trouble
with our Icelandic saga.

519
00:24:37,440 --> 00:24:39,120
Now, these people
are terribly keen,

520
00:24:39,160 --> 00:24:40,920
but they do rather tend
to take over.

521
00:24:40,960 --> 00:24:42,560
Um, I think I'd stick
to Caribbean Islands

522
00:24:42,600 --> 00:24:43,800
if I were you.

523
00:24:43,840 --> 00:24:45,920
Fine.

524
00:24:45,960 --> 00:24:48,320
And now, uh, back to the saga.

525
00:24:48,360 --> 00:24:50,800
[♪♪♪]

526
00:25:04,040 --> 00:25:07,440
Here. This is not Paris.
This is Iceland.

527
00:25:07,480 --> 00:25:09,520
Oh.

528
00:25:09,560 --> 00:25:13,240
Well, Paris must
be over there, then.

529
00:25:13,280 --> 00:25:15,160
Oh.

530
00:25:15,200 --> 00:25:16,840
[BOTH HUM]

531
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:21,520
[♪♪♪]

532
00:25:37,560 --> 00:25:40,160
Oh, here we are,
number 25.

533
00:25:40,200 --> 00:25:42,000
Oh, yes.

534
00:25:42,040 --> 00:25:45,640
"Flat 1, Yves Montand,
Flat 3, Jacques Cousteau.

535
00:25:45,680 --> 00:25:48,200
Flat 4, Jean Genet
and friend."

536
00:25:48,240 --> 00:25:50,400
BOTH:
Ooh! Ah! Yes.

537
00:25:50,440 --> 00:25:52,800
MRS. CONCLUSION:
"Flat 5, Maurice Leroux"?

538
00:25:52,840 --> 00:25:54,600
-Who's he?
-Never heard of him.

539
00:25:54,640 --> 00:25:58,480
"Flat 6, Marcel Marceau,
Walking Against the Wind Ltd.

540
00:25:58,520 --> 00:26:00,720
Flat 7, Indira Gandhi"?

541
00:26:00,760 --> 00:26:02,040
She gets about a bit,
doesn't she?

542
00:26:02,080 --> 00:26:03,800
BOTH:
Yes.

543
00:26:03,840 --> 00:26:07,040
"Flat 8, Jean-Paul
and Betty-Muriel Sartre."

544
00:26:07,080 --> 00:26:09,160
[INTERCOM BUZZES]

545
00:26:09,200 --> 00:26:10,760
BETTY [OVER INTERCOM]
Oui?

546
00:26:10,800 --> 00:26:13,240
[SPEAKS FRENCH]

547
00:26:16,360 --> 00:26:17,560
<i>Okay.</i>

548
00:26:17,600 --> 00:26:19,000
<i>Oui, merci.</i>

549
00:26:23,320 --> 00:26:26,080
[MAN SINGS IN FRENCH
OVER RADIO]

550
00:26:26,120 --> 00:26:29,080
[RASPY COUGH]

551
00:26:29,120 --> 00:26:30,920
[KNOCK]
Oh, rubbish.

552
00:26:30,960 --> 00:26:32,800
[CLEARS THROAT]

553
00:26:32,840 --> 00:26:34,000
<i>Bonjour.</i>

554
00:26:34,040 --> 00:26:35,720
<i>Parlez-vous anglais ?</i>

555
00:26:35,760 --> 00:26:37,400
Oh, yes. Good day.

556
00:26:37,440 --> 00:26:39,680
Hello, love.

557
00:26:39,720 --> 00:26:41,320
Hello, how are you?

558
00:26:41,360 --> 00:26:44,080
Oh, this is Mrs. Conclusion
from number 46.

559
00:26:44,120 --> 00:26:45,720
-Oh, nice to meet you, dear.
-Hello.

560
00:26:45,760 --> 00:26:47,320
How's the old man, then?

561
00:26:47,360 --> 00:26:50,560
Oh, don't ask. He's in one
of his bleeding moods.

562
00:26:50,600 --> 00:26:53,800
"The bourgeoisie this
is the bourgeoisie that."

563
00:26:53,840 --> 00:26:55,760
He's like a little child
sometimes.

564
00:26:55,800 --> 00:26:57,560
[COUGHS]

565
00:26:57,600 --> 00:26:59,160
I was only telling
the Rainiers the other day--

566
00:26:59,200 --> 00:27:00,680
Of course, he's always rude
to them,

567
00:27:00,720 --> 00:27:02,920
only classy friends we got.

568
00:27:02,960 --> 00:27:04,880
I was saying,
"Solidarity with the masses."

569
00:27:04,920 --> 00:27:06,920
I said, "Pie in the sky!"

570
00:27:06,960 --> 00:27:08,840
[LAUGHS]

571
00:27:08,880 --> 00:27:11,000
Oh, you're not a Marxist,
are you, Mrs. Conclusion?

572
00:27:11,040 --> 00:27:12,640
No, I'm a Revisionist.

573
00:27:12,680 --> 00:27:14,720
Oh, good.
I mean, look at this place.

574
00:27:14,760 --> 00:27:16,120
I'm at my wits' end.

575
00:27:16,160 --> 00:27:18,600
Revolutionary leaflets
everywhere.

576
00:27:18,640 --> 00:27:21,080
One of these days
I'll revolutionary
leaflets him.

577
00:27:21,120 --> 00:27:22,800
[ALL LAUGH]

578
00:27:22,840 --> 00:27:24,480
If it wasn't for the goat,

579
00:27:24,520 --> 00:27:26,640
you couldn't get in here
for propaganda.

580
00:27:26,680 --> 00:27:29,920
Oh, very well. Can we, uh,
pop in and have a word
with him?

581
00:27:29,960 --> 00:27:31,440
-Yes, come along.
-Thank you.

582
00:27:31,480 --> 00:27:34,240
But be careful.
He's had a few.

583
00:27:34,280 --> 00:27:36,120
Mind you, he's good as gold
in the morning,

584
00:27:36,160 --> 00:27:37,960
I've got to hand it to him.

585
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:40,600
But come lunchtime,
it's a bottle of
vin ordinaire.

586
00:27:40,640 --> 00:27:43,680
Six glasses
and he's ready to agitate.

587
00:27:43,720 --> 00:27:46,120
Uh, coo-ee!

588
00:27:46,160 --> 00:27:48,400
Jean-Paul?

589
00:27:48,440 --> 00:27:51,240
Jean-Paul?
Uh, it's only us.

590
00:27:51,280 --> 00:27:52,960
Oh, pardon.<i> C'est mêême nous.</i>

591
00:27:53,000 --> 00:27:54,600
-JEAN-PAUL:<i> Oui.</i>
-Jean-Paul,

592
00:27:54,640 --> 00:27:57,320
your famous trilogy
<i>Rues àà Liberté.</i>

593
00:27:57,360 --> 00:27:59,200
Is it an allegory
of man's search
for commitment?

594
00:27:59,240 --> 00:28:00,880
-JEAN-PAUL:<i> Oui.</i>
-Told you so.

595
00:28:00,920 --> 00:28:02,800
Oh, coitus.

596
00:28:02,840 --> 00:28:04,880
[♪♪♪]

597
00:28:17,160 --> 00:28:19,720
Today, we look
at a vanishing race.

598
00:28:19,760 --> 00:28:22,760
A problem people who are fast
disappearing

599
00:28:22,800 --> 00:28:24,720
off the face of the earth.

600
00:28:24,760 --> 00:28:28,360
A race who, one might say,
are losing a winning battle.

601
00:28:28,400 --> 00:28:32,040
They live in a sunshine
paradise, a Caribbean dream,

602
00:28:32,080 --> 00:28:34,680
where only reality is missing.

603
00:28:34,720 --> 00:28:37,120
For this is Whicker Island.

604
00:28:37,160 --> 00:28:41,560
An island inhabited entirely
by ex-international
interviewers

605
00:28:41,600 --> 00:28:44,400
in pursuit
of the impossible dream.

606
00:28:44,440 --> 00:28:47,080
The whole problem
of Whicker Island

607
00:28:47,120 --> 00:28:48,760
is here in a nutshell.

608
00:28:48,800 --> 00:28:50,560
There are just too many
whickers.

609
00:28:50,600 --> 00:28:52,400
The lightweight suits.

610
00:28:52,440 --> 00:28:54,480
The old-school tie.

611
00:28:54,520 --> 00:28:57,600
The practiced voice
of the seasoned campaigner...

612
00:28:57,640 --> 00:29:00,840
Cannot hide
the basic tragedy here.

613
00:29:00,880 --> 00:29:04,680
There just aren't enough
rich people left to interview.

614
00:29:04,720 --> 00:29:07,440
You can't teach an old dog
new tricks,

615
00:29:07,480 --> 00:29:09,120
and so you find them...

616
00:29:09,160 --> 00:29:12,320
Sitting beside
elegant swimming pools...

617
00:29:12,360 --> 00:29:14,000
Sipping martinis...

618
00:29:14,040 --> 00:29:17,560
And waiting
for the inevitable interview.

619
00:29:17,600 --> 00:29:22,400
I talked to the island's
only white man, Father Pierre.

620
00:29:22,440 --> 00:29:25,000
Father Pierre,
why did you stay on

621
00:29:25,040 --> 00:29:26,960
in this colonial Campari-land

622
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:28,640
where the clink of glasses
mingles

623
00:29:28,680 --> 00:29:30,760
with the murmur
of a million mosquitoes,

624
00:29:30,800 --> 00:29:33,080
where waterfalls
of whisky wash away

625
00:29:33,120 --> 00:29:35,280
the worries of
a world-weary whicker?

626
00:29:35,320 --> 00:29:38,640
Where gin-and-tonics jingle
in a gyroscopic jubilee

627
00:29:38,680 --> 00:29:40,440
of something
beginning with J?

628
00:29:40,480 --> 00:29:43,560
Father Pierre,
why did you stay on here?

629
00:29:43,600 --> 00:29:46,840
Well, mainly
for the interviews.

630
00:29:46,880 --> 00:29:49,160
Well, there you have it.

631
00:29:49,200 --> 00:29:50,560
A crumbling...

632
00:29:50,600 --> 00:29:52,560
Empire in the sun-drenched...

633
00:29:52,600 --> 00:29:55,800
Caribbean, where the clichés
sparkle on the waters...

634
00:29:55,840 --> 00:29:57,560
Like the music of repeat fees.

635
00:29:57,600 --> 00:29:58,840
And so...

636
00:29:58,880 --> 00:30:00,240
From Whicker Island...

637
00:30:00,280 --> 00:30:01,400
-It's...
-Fare...

638
00:30:01,440 --> 00:30:03,000
-Well and...
-Bon...

639
00:30:03,040 --> 00:30:04,760
-Voy...
-Age.

640
00:30:04,800 --> 00:30:06,800
[♪♪♪]
